Attention-Based Multivariate Time Series Forecasting Using Deep Learning

Objective

The objective of this project is to design and evaluate an attention-based deep learning model for multivariate time series forecasting and compare its performance against a standard LSTM baseline.

Dataset

A synthetic multivariate time series with more than 3000 observations and 5 features was generated using NumPy. The dataset includes trend, multiple seasonal patterns, non-linear interactions, and noise to simulate real-world temporal behavior.

Methodology

Two models were implemented:

LSTM as a baseline sequence model.

Transformer Encoder with self-attention to capture long-range temporal dependencies.

Walk-forward validation was applied to avoid data leakage. Performance was evaluated using MAE, RMSE, and MASE metrics.

Results

The Transformer model consistently achieved lower MAE, RMSE, and MASE values compared to the LSTM, indicating better forecasting accuracy.

Attention Analysis

Attention weights were visualized using heatmaps. The model focused more on recent time steps while also attending to periodic patterns, showing that the attention mechanism learned meaningful temporal dependencies.

Conclusion

The results demonstrate that attention-based models outperform traditional recurrent architectures for complex multivariate time series forecasting and provide improved interpretability through attention visualization
